101
00:08:54,583 --> 00:08:59,907
And in order to get the right message on the pop-up, we added Pepe Agency to the pilot.

102
00:09:04,388 --> 00:09:08,972
Yes, so some of you might be thinking, why social and emotional learning?

103
00:09:09,112 --> 00:09:12,454
What is that and how can that be used to reduce toxicity?

104
00:09:13,475 --> 00:09:18,239
Well, to start off, when we're using traditional methods like banning players,

105
00:09:19,380 --> 00:09:23,162
we're risking to leave them feeling perhaps even more frustrated

106
00:09:24,063 --> 00:09:26,005
or unaware of their hurtful behavior.

107
00:09:27,473 --> 00:09:30,155
To give you a comparison, I'm sure many of us in here

108
00:09:30,515 --> 00:09:32,977
have found ourselves in moments when we've lashed out

109
00:09:33,057 --> 00:09:36,119
either at our partner, our kids, or maybe a friend.

110
00:09:36,960 --> 00:09:38,421
And in the moment after, we thought,

111
00:09:38,561 --> 00:09:40,262
oh gosh, why did I do that?

112
00:09:41,443 --> 00:09:43,464
And so what if you would had a little person

113
00:09:43,504 --> 00:09:45,105
on your shoulder that told you,

114
00:09:45,125 --> 00:09:49,288
hey Paulina, why don't you stop and think for a moment?

115
00:09:50,933 --> 00:09:54,274
I'm sure that our behaviour would have been completely different.

116
00:09:55,054 --> 00:10:00,076
And that was the exact feeling that we wanted to provide players on Star Stable.

117
00:10:00,856 --> 00:10:06,418
To give them guidance to change their behaviour so that they could form positive relationships.

118
00:10:07,759 --> 00:10:12,880
And we saw that moment as a skill-building opportunity, but it was important that we

119
00:10:12,940 --> 00:10:14,861
did not judge their current behaviour.

120
00:10:18,152 --> 00:10:23,777
And the skills that we wanted to install are not only about being able to label your emotions

121
00:10:23,917 --> 00:10:28,681
and the feelings that you're feeling in that heated moment, it's also about understanding

122
00:10:28,821 --> 00:10:34,486
other people's emotions and how you can use that information to form positive and healthy

123
00:10:34,546 --> 00:10:35,326
relationships.

124
00:10:38,009 --> 00:10:42,532
Now, when we design, we have a principle to design with empathy.

125
00:10:43,173 --> 00:10:46,936
And in this case, we needed to go to the root of why people bully.

126
00:10:48,193 --> 00:10:52,716
In many cases, it's because you feel unhappy, scared, or unheard.

127
00:10:53,396 --> 00:10:57,719
It might be because of something that happened at home, or it could be something that happened

128
00:10:57,739 --> 00:10:58,159
in the game.

129
00:10:59,400 --> 00:11:05,264
It might also be that I lack the skills to control my impulses or to label my emotions.

130
00:11:07,105 --> 00:11:11,988
And in the case of Star Stable, which I think is true for many online games, we could see

131
00:11:12,108 --> 00:11:15,711
that players were acting out of rage when they lost a race.

132
00:11:16,934 --> 00:11:21,116
Or perhaps they spotted bullying in a chat, but they were too afraid to act,

133
00:11:21,536 --> 00:11:26,919
and they might even continue and tag along with the friends in the behavior that they could see.

134
00:11:28,639 --> 00:11:32,861
We could also see that players felt disappointed about a recent release,

135
00:11:33,021 --> 00:11:34,862
and they acted out in that frustration.

136
00:11:37,181 --> 00:11:42,822
So with this knowledge and the awareness of what situation a player might find him or

137
00:11:42,862 --> 00:11:48,723
herself in when they're acting in their anger, we developed a three-step approach that is

138
00:11:48,783 --> 00:11:55,424
based on a research-based method called non-violent communication. And we divided it into three

139
00:11:55,484 --> 00:12:01,445
steps where the first one is to help the player identify his or her feelings and the situation

140
00:12:01,505 --> 00:12:03,526
that we would like that person to change.

141
00:12:04,707 --> 00:12:07,730
So we talk about self-awareness and self-management.

142
00:12:08,691 --> 00:12:11,193
The second step is to help the player understand

143
00:12:11,273 --> 00:12:14,396
how the hurtful behavior is causing others to feel.

144
00:12:14,956 --> 00:12:16,137
So social awareness.

145
00:12:17,058 --> 00:12:20,781
And then we wanted to encourage a more positive behavior

146
00:12:20,921 --> 00:12:25,285
by giving an example of what that player could do.

147
00:12:25,805 --> 00:12:27,907
So talking about relationship building.

148
00:12:29,628 --> 00:12:30,970
And in the case of Star Stable,

149
00:12:31,090 --> 00:12:33,272
this is the message that we ended up using.

150
00:12:34,232 --> 00:12:38,273
So first you see, hey, it seems you sent an unkind message.

151
00:12:38,833 --> 00:12:41,574
We're helping the player identify the behavior

152
00:12:41,614 --> 00:12:44,775
that we would like to change, but without judging.

153
00:12:46,255 --> 00:12:48,576
Secondly, stop and think, how would you feel

154
00:12:48,776 --> 00:12:50,037
if someone said that to you?

155
00:12:50,777 --> 00:12:54,938
So giving the player the opportunity to experience empathy

156
00:12:55,058 --> 00:12:59,179
and put themselves in the shoes of another player's feet.

157
00:13:00,473 --> 00:13:04,755
And then third, remember, being a good friend can also get you lots of new friends.

158
00:13:05,036 --> 00:13:06,877
So why would I change my behavior?

159
00:13:06,917 --> 00:13:09,658
Well, if I can get new friends, that sounds pretty good.

160
00:13:11,299 --> 00:13:16,943
Now the message would not be effective if we couldn't identify the right moments to

